@node "System" "What do you need ?"

@{b}         Artificial Intelligence manual@{ub}
Documentation version 1.1 written on 16 September 2000

Running a simulation will require the following things:

@{b} Amiga computer@{ub}
@{b} 4 MB free Fastram@{ub}
@{b} 68020+ processor@{ub}
@{b} AGA graphics@{ub}
@{b} Mouse@{ub}

Recommended is a 68030+ with 4+ MB fastram.

If you're having problems starting the program, please inform us.

@endnode


@rem -------------------------------------------------------

@node "Concept" "Artificial Intelligence concept"

@{b}         Artificial Intelligence manual@{ub}
Documentation version 1.1 written on 16 September 2000

The concept of this program is based on an algorithm which can analyze small
parts of a maze and walk through it. The algorithm has several parameters 
which can be altered before the simulation starts.

@{b}Altering the parameters@{ub}
All parameters can be changed if the simulation needs this. You can devide
the blocks for a proper AI installation. i.e. Walking requires less blocks 
compared to analyzing, so you should set all parameters you think are best.

@{b}Energy@{ub}
Analyzing the maze will require energy. If the routine has used all its energy
it will die. Thinking and walking requires energy, battle and mating requires more
energy. 

@{b}Analyzing capability@{ub}
The higher you set this number, the more steps the AI can analyze. More steps to
consider also requires more thinking time. A perfect brain will also analyse every 
possible solution which won't always be best due to the contest.

@{b}Analyzing power@{ub}
This setting will give the AI a faster set of brains which will defenitely come in
handy for a better analyzing brain.

@{b}Agression@{ub}
This setting changes the AI's approach to diferent species. Walking away is sometimes
the best possible solution and sometimes not.

@{b}Fertility@{ub}
Altering this will give the AI a better fertility factor which will come in handy for
the huge battles to come, since it needs more friends in battle. Overpopulation will
also give a very unclear view of what is happening.

@{b}Blocks@{ub}
This figure will show you how many points you can devide for the settings.

@endnode

@rem -------------------------------------------------------

@node "Level1" "About level 1"

@{b}         Artificial Intelligence manual@{ub}
Documentation version 1.1 written on 16 September 2000

@{b}Level 1, the introduction@{ub}
This level contains a small maze with a single AI. The AI will immediatly try
to find the exit. Sometimes the exit is found straight away and sometimes it
can take ages. Everytime the AI has found the exit its awarded with a better
analyzing brain.

If you run this simulation you will notice the following things:

@{b}Confused@{ub}
The AI gets confused while its brain is growing. More memory will also be 
confused more easier. When its confused the AI will stop and analyze all 
data it knows. After this it will start walking again.

@{b}30 minute run@{ub}
When you've run the simulation for 30 minutes or longer you will notice the
AI is capable of finding the exit almost straight away. He's able to understand
the entire maze. If you think 30 minutes is a long time try to understand the
fact that the routine has actually created a solution which will always find
the exit. It has done that all by itself and you should love him for that!

@endnode

@node "Level2" "About level 2"

@{b}         Artificial Intelligence manual@{ub}
Documentation version 1.1 written on 16 September 2000

@{b}Level 2, the memory@{ub}
This level contains two AIs. The green AI has got a very reliable brain, the
pink AI's brain is very poor. You can compare the different memory to see what
a reliable brain means to the AI.

@{b}Pink seems smarter@{ub}
If the pink AI finds the exit before the green one it is lucky, even dummies 
can walk the right direction without knowing it's the right way. Run several 
simulations to verify this!

@{b}Green isn't looking very smart@{ub}
Although the green AI has a very reliable memory that won't mean it's analyzing
power is great. It will only recognize different positions and locations easier 
than the pink one.

@endnode

@node "Level3" "About level 3"

@{b}         Artificial Intelligence manual@{ub}
Documentation version 1.1 written on 16 September 2000

@{b}Level 3, Experience yourself@{ub}
This level will give you the opportunity to get to know each different 
parameter. Play with the different settings and try to understand what is
happening. The maze is quite huge so it will be fun to play with.

@{b}Tips@{ub}
Try to see what a the AI does when it's walking to the end of a corner, if the 
AI walks into the corner again towards the end it must have forgotten it was
there before. With a reliable memory you will see the AI turn away from it when
it realises it has been there before. 

Setting the analyse power to a high factor will give the AI the ability to 
analyze the maze without moving. If it isn't walking it's trying to figure out
how to get to the exit. When it suddenly moves but is going into the wrong
direction it means that it's memory was full.

@endnode


@node "Level4" "About level 4"

@{b}         Artificial Intelligence manual@{ub}
Documentation version 1.1 written on 16 September 2000

@{b}Level 4, No exit@{ub}
This level contains two AIs. The green AI has got a very reliable brain, the
pink AI's brain are very poor. You can compare the different memory to see what
a reliable brain means for the AI.

This time you will actually see the difference between the two memory's of the
AI. Since the AI can't reach the exit you will clearly see that the reliable 
memory will remember far more and also lead to a conclusion that there is NO 
exit. The pink AI will forget lots of value information and thus never know the
exit isn't reachable. 

If you still had any doubts about level 2 this level will surely show you what 
a reliable memory means. Although it can take quite a while for the AI to
understand the maze!

@endnode

@node "Level5" "About level 5"

@{b}         Artificial Intelligence manual@{ub}
Documentation version 1.1 written on 16 September 2000

@{b}Level 5, Mating@{ub}
Sometimes smart can be defeated by an overwelming enemy. You're facing a very 
fast reproducing enemy who will defeat you if your population isn't growing fast
enough. Try to reach the exit and let your population grow to defeat the enemy.

@{b}Note@{ub}
The black spicies can be compared to germs, stupid but fast reproduction. The 
only possible way to defeat these germs is to get your AI to the exit so that
it knows were to find his family. If they found eachoder they can reproduce
aswell and hopefully defeat the black germs.



@endnode

@node "Level6" "About level 6"

@{b}         Artificial Intelligence manual@{ub}
Documentation version 1.1 written on 16 September 2000

@{b}Level 6, It's WAR@{ub}
Now that you have seen all posibilities try to win this level, no clues are
given! Have fun and don't forget to inform HellHound about your experiences.

If you want to play more with the simulator you should wait until the 
level-creater program is finished. It's kinda depending on the positive mails
for this because we're also working on several other projects. But you will 
defenitly find this algorithm in some of our other projects.

At this point I would like to ask you to send us how you experienced playing
with this simulator.

Send it all to: hcoder@hellhound.root.nl
Thank you!

@endnode

